"""mkt-original: Daniel 9–11
Type: original
Book: daniel
Chapters: 9–11
Run: python3 scripts/zc-original-daniel-9-11-fill.py

Ch 9: Daniel's prayer (vv.1-19) + Gabriel's seventy-weeks oracle (vv.20-27).
  Key terms: shivim shavuim (seventy sevens), mashiach nagid (anointed prince),
  yikaret (cut off), selichot/rachamim (forgivenesses/mercies), tsedaqah.
Ch 10: The visionary prologue — three-week fast, man clothed in linen (divine figure),
  heavenly battle with sar Paras / sar Yavan. Key terms: ish lavush badim,
  sar (prince of nations), emet (book of truth), b'acharit hayamim.
Ch 11: The detailed prophetic overview — Persian kings, Alexander (gibor), wars of
  the Diadochi, Antiochus IV (niv'zeh, shiquts meshomem, maskilei am).

Note: ch 9 v.24 already present from combined seed script; all other verses are new.
Note: Daniel 2:4b-7:28 is in Aramaic; chs 8-12 revert to Hebrew.
  Where Aramaic terms appear they are labeled (Aram.) in entries.
"""
import json, pathlib
ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(layer, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / layer / f'{book}.json'
    return json.loads(p.read_text()) if p.exists() else {}

def save_comm(layer, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / layer / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

NEW_DATA = {
"9": {
"1": "<p><strong>bishnat achat leDaryavesh ben Achashverosh mizzera Madai</strong> (<em>bišnat ʾaḥat lĕdāryāwēš ben ʾăḥašwērôš mizzeraʿ māday</em>): 'In the first year of Darius son of Ahasuerus, of Median descent.' The dating formula is precise: Darius (identity debated — either a secondary title for Cyrus or an otherwise unrecorded official) is identified by parentage and ethnicity. <em>Mizzera Madai</em> (of Median seed) situates Daniel's prayer in the Medo-Persian transition, the moment when the seventy-year prophecy of Jeremiah (9:2) is approaching fulfillment. The historical precision grounds the prayer in real time — Daniel calculates the prophetic clock.</p>",
"2": "<p><strong>binah b'sefarim</strong> (<em>bînāh bĕsĕpārîm</em>): 'understood from the scrolls/books.' <em>Binah</em> (H998) is not merely reading but interpretive understanding — the same root as the heavenly figure's instruction to Daniel to understand (<em>hitbonen</em>, v.23). <em>Sefarim</em> (scrolls) refers to the written prophetic corpus already circulating as authoritative texts; Daniel treats Jeremiah's prophecy as canonical Scripture. <em>Shivim shanah</em> (seventy years): Jer 25:11-12 and 29:10 — Daniel is calculating the prophetic timeline. This is one of the earliest explicit examples of prophetic interpretation of prior prophecy, establishing the tradition of inner-biblical exegesis.</p>",
"3": "<p><strong>etten et-panai el-Adonai ha'Elohim</strong> (<em>ʾettēn ʾet-pānay ʾel-ʾădōnāy hāʾĕlōhîm</em>): 'I set my face toward the Lord God.' <em>Natan panim</em> (set the face) is a Hebrew idiom for deliberate, focused orientation — the whole self directed toward God in covenantal address. The prayer disciplines listed — <em>tsom</em> (fasting), <em>saq</em> (sackcloth), <em>efer</em> (ashes) — are the classic triad of covenant mourning, mirroring Jonah 3:6 and Esther 4:1-3. Daniel mourns over the covenant's broken condition before he prays for its restoration, establishing penitence as the necessary posture for effective intercessory prayer.</p>",
"4": "<p><strong>el gadol venora shomer haberit vehahesed</strong> (<em>ʾēl gādôl wĕnôrāʾ šômēr habbĕrît wĕhahesed</em>): 'great and awesome God who keeps the covenant and steadfast love.' Daniel's prayer opens with YHWH's covenant-character as the basis for appeal — not human merit but divine attribute. <em>Nora</em> (awesome/fearsome): the same term used in Exod 34:10; Deut 10:21. <em>Shomer haberit vehahesed</em>: the covenant-keeping formula from the Deuteronomic blessing tradition (Deut 7:9, 12), invoked here as the ground of Daniel's hope. Prayer appeals to who God is, not what Israel deserves.</p>",
"5": "<p><strong>chatanu va'avinu hirshanu umradnu vesor mimitzvotecha</strong> (<em>ḥāṭāʾnû wĕʿāwînû hirŝaʿnû ûmāradnû wĕsôr mimmitswōtêkā</em>): 'We have sinned and done wrong and acted wickedly and rebelled and turned aside from your commandments.' Daniel deploys five Hebrew sin-verbs in rapid sequence — one of the most comprehensive sin-catalogues in Scripture. <em>Chata</em> (H2398, miss the mark), <em>avah</em> (H5753, twist/pervert), <em>hirshia</em> (H7561, act wickedly/be in the wrong), <em>marad</em> (H4775, rebel openly), <em>sur</em> (H5493, turn aside/deviate). This is not rhetorical accumulation but theological precision: sin is simultaneously moral failure, relational distortion, covenantal rebellion, and directional deviation.</p>",
"6": "<p><strong>velo shamanu el-avadecha haneviim</strong> (<em>wĕlōʾ šāmaʿnû ʾel-ʿăbādêkā hannĕbîʾîm</em>): 'We did not listen to your servants the prophets.' <em>Shama</em> (H8085) is simultaneously to hear and to obey — non-listening is non-obedience. The phrase <em>avadecha haneviim</em> (your servants the prophets) is the characteristic Deuteronomistic designation for the prophetic office (2 Kgs 9:7; 17:13, 23; Amos 3:7; Jer 7:25). The chain — YHWH sent, prophets spoke, Israel refused to hear — identifies the theological mechanism of the exile: covenantal deafness to the divine word.</p>",
"7": "<p><strong>lecha Adonai hatsedaqah velanu bosheth hapanim</strong> (<em>lĕkā ʾădōnāy haṣṣĕdāqāh wĕlānû bôšet happānîm</em>): 'To you, Lord, belongs righteousness; to us shame of face.' The antithesis is theologically precise: <em>tsedaqah</em> (H6666) here is YHWH's covenant-faithfulness and rectifying justice — the quality by which he acts consistently with his own covenant character. <em>Bosheth hapanim</em> (shame of face) is a Semitic idiom for public disgrace and dishonor. The exile is the visible manifestation of this shame — Israel's covenantal failure exposed before the nations. Daniel prays not by hiding this but by owning it as the starting point for covenantal appeal.</p>",
"8": "<p><strong>lanu bosheth hapanim lamelachim leshareinu uleavoteinu asher chatanu lach</strong>: 'To us belongs shame of face — to our kings, our officials, and our fathers who sinned against you.' The scope of the confession is comprehensive: shame belongs to every stratum of Israelite society — monarchy, administration, and the ancestral heritage. Daniel does not exempt the leadership from the communal confession; the exile is a systemic failure, not merely individual lapses. The solidarity of confession — <em>chatanu lach</em> (we sinned against you) — is the model of corporate representative prayer that shapes later Jewish liturgy.</p>",
"9": "<p><strong>laAdonai Eloheinu harachamim vehaselichot ki maradnu bo</strong> (<em>laʾădōnāy ʾĕlōhênû hāraḥămîm wĕhasslîḥôt kî māradnû bô</em>): 'To the Lord our God belong mercy and forgiveness, for we have rebelled against him.' <em>Rachamim</em> (H7356, mercies/compassions): plural intensive of <em>rechem</em> (womb) — YHWH's compassion is as intimate and unconditional as a mother's for her child (Isa 49:15). <em>Selichot</em> (H5547, forgivenesses): plural, occurring only three times in the OT (Neh 9:17; Ps 130:4; here) — the plural emphasizes the inexhaustible character of divine forgiveness. The logic is daring: because we have rebelled, YHWH's forgiveness-quality is now the only hope.</p>",
"10": "<p><strong>velo shamanu beqol YHWH Eloheinu lalechet betorotav</strong>: 'We did not listen to the voice of YHWH our God by walking in his laws.' The phrase <em>lalechet</em> (to walk) marks Torah-observance as a mode of life — halakha (from <em>halakh</em>, walk) later becomes the rabbinic technical term for the whole body of practical commandments. Not listening to the divine voice is not an abstract theological failure but a behavioral deviation — Israel's feet went the wrong direction. The Torah given through Moses and the subsequent prophets is the road; Israel refused to walk it.</p>",
"11": "<p><strong>nitach aleinu ha'alah</strong> (<em>nittaḥ ʿālênû hāʾālāh</em>): 'The curse has been poured out upon us.' <em>Alah</em> (H423) is specifically the covenantal oath-curse — the treaty-curse that YHWH swore would come if Israel broke the covenant (Deut 28:15-68; Lev 26:14-43). The exile is the alah-sanction activated: not random misfortune but the precise covenantal consequence that Moses and the prophets had warned of. <em>Nitach</em> (poured out) — the same pouring-out language used for libation offerings is here applied to curse — the covenant has been poured out in judgment rather than blessing.</p>",
"12": "<p><strong>vayaqem et-devarav asher diber aleinu</strong>: 'He confirmed his words that he spoke against us.' YHWH's faithfulness works in two directions: he keeps his covenant promises of blessing (v.4), and he keeps his covenant threats of curse. The exile is proof of YHWH's consistency — his word is reliable even when it falls as judgment. This theological point is important: Israel cannot claim YHWH's promises while denying his warnings. Daniel's prayer acknowledges that YHWH acted justly in bringing the disaster — the prophets' warnings were true.</p>",
"13": "<p><strong>velo challinu et-penei YHWH Eloheinu lashuv meavoneinu</strong>: 'We did not entreat the face of YHWH our God, turning from our iniquities.' <em>Challah et-panim</em> (H2470 + H6440, entreat/pacify the face of) is the idiom for seeking divine favor through prayer and repentance. <em>Lashuv</em> (to return/repent): <em>shuv</em> (H7725) is the primary Hebrew repentance term — a turning-of-direction, not merely an internal feeling. The failure was not primarily intellectual (they did not understand the Torah rightly) but volitional: they knew but did not turn. <em>Velo haskilnu be'amitecha</em> (not attending to your truth) — <em>emet</em> as truth/faithfulness is the ground of prayer.</p>",
"14": "<p><strong>vayishkod YHWH al-hara'ah vayevi'iha aleinu</strong>: 'YHWH was watchful over the disaster and brought it upon us.' <em>Shaqad</em> (H8245, be watchful/alert) is the same root as the almond (<em>shaqed</em>) imagery in Jer 1:11-12 — YHWH is watching to perform his word. The disaster was not YHWH sleeping or ignoring; he was actively watching to execute his just judgment. <em>Ki-tsaddiq YHWH Eloheinu al-kol-ma'asav asher asah ve'lo shamanu b'qolo</em>: YHWH is righteous (<em>tsaddiq</em>) in all he has done — the exile vindicated rather than indicted YHWH's character.</p>",
"15": "<p><strong>ve'attah Adonai Eloheinu asher hotzeta et-amcha me'eretz Mitsraim beyad chazaqah</strong>: 'And now, Lord our God, who brought your people out of Egypt with a mighty hand.' The pivot from confession to petition is bridged by the Exodus appeal — YHWH's paradigmatic act of salvation. <em>Yad chazaqah</em> (mighty hand) is the standard Deuteronomic descriptor for the Exodus (Deut 4:34; 5:15; 7:8). Just as YHWH delivered from Egypt, so he can deliver from Babylon. The prayer's logic: the same God who acted then can act now, and his name's reputation is at stake in both cases.</p>",
"16": "<p><strong>bechol-tsidqotecha yashuv-na aphcha chamatha</strong>: 'In all your acts of righteousness, let your anger and wrath turn away.' <em>Tsidqotecha</em> (your righteousnesses): plural, referring to the accumulation of YHWH's saving acts in Israel's history — each rescue, each covenant renewal is an act of tsedaqah. These past acts are the basis for appealing to future action. The pairing of <em>aph</em> (burning anger) and <em>chamah</em> (wrath/heat) is the standard merism for divine anger — Daniel does not minimize the reality of YHWH's wrath but appeals for its redirection from the city to YHWH's mercy.</p>",
"17": "<p><strong>shema Elohenu el-tefillat avdecha</strong>: 'Hear, our God, the prayer of your servant.' <em>Shema</em> at the prayer's climax echoes the Shema of Deut 6:4 — the same verb now turned back to God. Daniel prays that YHWH will hear as he commanded Israel to hear. <em>Veha'er panecha al-miqdashecha hashamem</em>: 'Let your face shine upon your desolated sanctuary.' The sanctuary's desolation is both the problem and the theological test — a desolate temple suggests an absent God. The prayer is that YHWH's luminous presence will return to the destroyed place, reversing the departure of the glory described in Ezekiel 10-11.</p>",
"18": "<p><strong>ki lo al-tsidqoteinu anachnu maphilim tachanunenu lefanecha</strong>: 'For it is not on account of our righteousness that we present our pleas before you.' The final ground-clearing: all appeal to human merit is renounced. <em>Tachanunenu</em> (our pleas/supplications) — <em>tachanun</em> from <em>chanan</em> (H2603, show favor/grace) — the prayer itself is an appeal for grace, not a claim of righteousness. <em>Ki al-rachamecha harabim</em>: 'but on account of your great mercies.' The prayer rests entirely on the divine attribute of <em>rachamim rabim</em> (great mercies) — what YHWH is by nature and covenant, not what Israel has earned.</p>",
"19": "<p><strong>Adonai shema Adonai selach Adonai haqshivah va'aseh al-te'acher</strong>: 'Lord, hear! Lord, forgive! Lord, listen and act! Do not delay!' The triple invocation of <em>Adonai</em> creates an urgent litany — each address adds a new petition: hearing, forgiveness, attentive action, and urgency. <em>Lemaan shimcha</em>: 'for your own name's sake' — the prayer's ultimate appeal is YHWH's reputation among the nations. <em>Ki shimcha nikra al-ircha ve'al-amecha</em>: your name is called over your city and your people — the name-theology of covenant means YHWH's honor is bound up with the destiny of Jerusalem and Israel.</p>",
"20": "<p><strong>vod ani medabber umitpallel</strong>: 'While I was still speaking and praying.' The immediacy of the divine response (Gabriel arrives while Daniel is still speaking, v.21) demonstrates that YHWH hears prayer in real time. <em>Matir chatati vachetat ami Yisrael</em>: 'confessing my sin and the sin of my people Israel' — the intercessory prayer model is Daniel's own sin bound up with the community's. The individual representative mediates for the corporate body — the pattern of all biblical intercession.</p>",
"21": "<p><strong>vehaish Gavriel asher ra'iti bachazoni batchillah muaf biye'af</strong>: 'The man Gabriel whom I had seen in the vision at the beginning, flying swiftly.' <em>Gavriel</em> (H1403) = <em>gavar</em> (H1368, mighty/strong) + <em>El</em> (God) — the mighty one of God. This is one of only four named angels in the canonical OT/NT (Gabriel, Michael, Raphael in Tobit, and Lucifer/Satan as adversarial figure). <em>Muaf biye'af</em>: the phrase for flight is debated — either flying with swiftness or approaching in a state of exhaustion/weariness. Either way, Gabriel's arrival is direct divine response to Daniel's prayer.</p>",
"22": "<p><strong>vayiven oti vayedabber immi vayomar Daniel atah yatsati lehaskil binah</strong>: 'He made me understand and spoke to me, saying: Daniel, I have now come out to give you insight and understanding.' <em>Lehaskil</em> (to give insight/make wise) and <em>binah</em> (understanding): both from roots associated with wisdom and discernment. Gabriel's mission is not merely information delivery but cognitive enhancement — the revelation opens Daniel's understanding to grasp what mere human reasoning cannot reach. This is the model of biblical revelation: God gives not just data but the interpretive capacity to receive it.</p>",
"23": "<p><strong>bithchillat tachanuneicha yatsa dabar vaani bati lehagid ki chamudot attah</strong>: 'At the beginning of your pleas a word went out, and I have come to tell you, for you are greatly beloved.' <em>Chamudot</em> (H2532, beloved/precious/desirable): Daniel is described as <em>ish chamudot</em> (beloved man) in 10:11, 19 as well — a term of divine affection. The timing — the word went out at the beginning of the prayer — indicates that YHWH's response was initiated immediately upon Daniel's prayer, not after waiting for its completion. Intercessory prayer is heard as it begins.</p>",
"25": "<p><strong>umeshiach nagid shavuim shiva uveshavuim shishim ushnayim</strong>: 'And from the going out of the word to restore and build Jerusalem to the coming of an anointed prince, there shall be seven weeks. And for sixty-two weeks it shall be built again.' <em>Mashiach nagid</em> (anointed prince): <em>mashiach</em> is the anointed one — used for priests (Lev 4:3), kings (1 Sam 16:6; Ps 2:2), and here the expected eschatological figure. <em>Nagid</em> (H5057, prince/leader/commander) is a royal term. The mathematical structure (7 + 62 + 1 = 70 weeks) has generated centuries of calculation; the referents remain debated. The key theological point: YHWH has decreed a specific redemptive timeline, and the anointed one's coming is the center of the seventy-week period.</p>",
"26": "<p><strong>yikaret mashiach ve'ein lo</strong> (<em>yikkārēt māšîaḥ wĕʾên lô</em>): 'The anointed one will be cut off and will have nothing (or: not for himself).' <em>Karet</em> (H3772, cut off/cut down) is the standard Torah term for judicial death and covenant exclusion (used for capital offenses: Exod 31:14; Lev 7:20-21; Num 15:30-31). <em>Ve'ein lo</em> is ambiguous: either the anointed one receives nothing (no kingdom, no inheritance) or the cutting off is not for himself (i.e., not for his own sin — the same construction as Isa 53:8's <em>mipesha ammi nega lamo</em>). The latter reading aligns with Isaiah's Servant dying for others, not for his own transgressions.</p>",
"27": "<p><strong>vehigbir berit larabim shavua echad vachatsit hashavua yashbit zevach umincha</strong>: 'He shall make a strong covenant with many for one week, and for half of the week he shall put an end to sacrifice and offering.' <em>Higbir berit</em> (strengthen/confirm covenant): <em>gavar</em> (H1396, be strong/prevail) in Hiphil — to cause the covenant to prevail. <em>Larabim</em> (for the many) — the phrase echoes Isa 53:11-12 (<em>yatsdiq tsaddiq avdi larabim</em>, my righteous servant makes many righteous). <em>Shiquts meshomem</em> (abomination of desolation): <em>shiquts</em> (H8251, detestable thing/idol) + <em>meshomem</em> (H8074, causing desolation/stunned). This phrase (also 11:31; 12:11) becomes Jesus's own term for the end-time crisis (Mark 13:14 and parallels).</p>"
},
"10": {
"1": "<p><strong>dabar emet</strong> (<em>dābār ʾěmet</em>): 'a true word/message.' <em>Emet</em> (H571, truth/faithfulness/reliability) heads the characterization of the vision — this is not ambiguous prophecy but verified, faithful disclosure. The term <em>tsava gadol</em> (great conflict) signals that the vision concerns cosmic warfare beyond the political surface. Daniel mourning for three weeks (v.2-3) is a prolonged preparation for major revelation — cf. Moses on Sinai forty days (Exod 24:18).</p>",
"2": "<p><strong>hayiti mitabel shloshah shavuim yamim</strong>: 'I was mourning for three weeks of days.' <em>Mitabel</em> (H56, mourn): intense sustained grief — Daniel neither eats delicacies nor meat nor wine nor anoints himself for three weeks. The mourning is over the unresolved situation of the exile and the content of the Jeremiah-calculation (ch.9). The discipline of extended mourning-prayer as preparation for revelation is a model of prophetic intercession: the body's self-denial corresponds to the spirit's urgent seeking.</p>",
"3": "<p><strong>lechem chamudot lo achalti uvesar vayyayin lo ba bephi</strong>: 'I ate no delicacies, no meat or wine came to my mouth, nor did I anoint myself.' The three abstentions — pleasant food, meat, wine, anointing — reverse the court-feast context of Daniel 1:5. The same court setting that Daniel navigated in ch.1 is now voluntarily renounced in mourning. <em>Lechem chamudot</em> (desirable/pleasant bread) recalls the <em>chamudot</em> term applied to Daniel himself as the beloved one — here he abstains from what is desirable in order to seek the heavenly beloved.</p>",
"4": "<p><strong>vaani hayiti al-yad hanahar haGadol hu Deqel</strong>: 'I was on the bank of the great river, that is, the Tigris.' <em>Deqel</em> (Tigris) — the Tigris rather than the Euphrates as the setting of this vision, as opposed to the Ulai canal of ch. 8. The great rivers of the ancient Near East are consistently liminal spaces for divine encounter in the prophets: Ezekiel's Chebar canal (Ezek 1:1), Ezra's Ahava canal (Ezra 8:21). Rivers mark the boundary between ordinary and sacred space.</p>",
"5": "<p><strong>ish echad lavush badim umotanav chagur betaz Uphaz</strong>: 'A man clothed in linen, his waist girded with gold from Uphaz.' <em>Badim</em> (H906, linen): the priestly material par excellence — the high priest wore linen in the holy of holies (Lev 16:4); the divine attendants in Ezekiel's vision wore linen (Ezek 9:2; 10:6-7). The figure's clothing signals priestly-divine status. <em>Uphaz</em>: location uncertain — possibly equivalent to <em>Ophir</em> (H211), the OT's gold standard. The Revelation's Son of Man figure (Rev 1:13) wears the identical garment: <em>endedumenos podere</em> (clothed to the foot) with a golden girdle — a direct Danielic allusion.</p>",
"6": "<p><strong>gevo keTarshish ufanav kemareh baraq ve'einav kelappidei esh</strong>: 'His body was like Tarshish stone, his face was like the appearance of lightning, his eyes were like torches of fire.' <em>Tarshish</em> (H8658) is likely beryl/chrysolite — a gleaming, translucent green-blue gem. The sequence of cosmic comparisons — lightning-face, fire-eyes, burnished-bronze limbs, thunder-voice — marks the figure as superhuman, aligned with Ezekiel's divine chariot-throne imagery (Ezek 1:7, 13-14, 27). John's vision of the risen Christ (Rev 1:14-16) replicates these features exactly, identifying the Danielic heavenly figure with the glorified Son of Man.</p>",
"7": "<p><strong>velo ra'u et-hamareh ha'anashim asher hayu imi</strong>: 'The men who were with me did not see the vision.' The selectivity of prophetic vision — others nearby yet unseeing — parallels Paul's Damascus road experience (Acts 9:7: men heard the voice but saw nothing; Acts 22:9: saw the light but did not hear the voice). The inability of ordinary perception to receive extraordinary divine disclosure is a consistent feature of biblical theophany: vision is given to those prepared to receive it.</p>",
"8": "<p><strong>ve'ani nisharthi levaddi va'ereh et-hamareh hagedolah hazot velo nithar bi koach vehodi nehavkha alai lemashchit</strong>: 'I was left alone and saw this great vision, and no strength remained in me; my radiant appearance was fearfully changed.' <em>Hod</em> (H1935, majesty/radiance/splendor) — the same term used for Moses's face-radiance after encountering YHWH (Exod 34:29 uses <em>qaran</em>, but <em>hod</em> describes the residual divine glory in figures). The contact with divine majesty depletes human vitality — the body cannot sustain the proximity of the holy. This is not illness but the finite's response to the infinite.</p>",
"9": "<p><strong>va'eshma et-qol devarav uveshomyi et-qol devarav hayiti nirdam</strong>: 'I heard the sound of his words, and when I heard the sound of his words I fell into a deep sleep on my face.' <em>Qol devarav</em> (sound/voice of his words): the heavenly voice as overwhelming sonic force — the same as Ezekiel's voice like many waters (Ezek 1:24). <em>Nirdam</em> (H7290, fell into deep sleep): not ordinary sleep but the stupor of prophetic trance, parallel to the <em>tardemah</em> (deep sleep) that fell on Abraham at the covenant ceremony (Gen 15:12). The posture — face to the ground — is the standard theophany response.</p>",
"10": "<p><strong>vehinei yad nag'ah vi vatenioani al-birkai vekaph yadai</strong>: 'And behold, a hand touched me and set me trembling on my hands and knees.' The sequence of restoration — touch, rising to knees and hands, then upright (v.11) — is a measured reinstatement of the prophet's capacity to receive the revelation. The divine touch that prostrates (overwhelming glory) and restores (enabling grace) is the pattern of all prophetic commissioning: Moses at the burning bush, Isaiah before the throne, Paul on the Damascus road.</p>",
"11": "<p><strong>ish chamudot bina bidevari</strong>: 'O man greatly beloved, understand the words that I speak to you.' This is the second occurrence of <em>ish chamudot</em> (man of desirings/beloved man) — Daniel is identified by his belovedness as the qualifier for receiving revelation. <em>Bina</em> (H998, understand/discern) — the imperative to discern, not merely receive, marks the prophetic task. Understanding requires active engagement, not passive reception.</p>",
"12": "<p><strong>al-tira Daniel ki min-hayom harishon asher natata et-libbecha lehavin velehitanot lifnei Eloheicha nishmeu devareicha</strong>: 'Do not be afraid, Daniel, for from the first day that you set your heart to understand and to humble yourself before your God, your words have been heard.' <em>Natata et-libbecha</em> (set your heart): <em>lev</em> (heart) as the whole inner life directed toward understanding. <em>Lehitanot</em> (to humble yourself): the reflexive Hitpael of <em>anah</em> — self-humbling as the disposition that opens heavenly access. The revelation was triggered on day one; the twenty-one-day delay was due to cosmic resistance (v.13), not divine inattention.</p>",
"13": "<p><strong>sar malkhut Paras omed lenegdi echad ve'esrim yom</strong>: 'The prince of the kingdom of Persia stood in opposition against me for twenty-one days.' <em>Sar</em> (H8269, prince/captain/commander) as a cosmic role — each nation has a heavenly <em>sar</em> (angelic guardian) corresponding to its earthly political identity. This doctrine of national angels (cf. Deut 32:8 LXX, which assigns nations to the <em>sons of God</em>; 1 Enoch 20) explains the geopolitical conflicts of history as having a heavenly dimension. <em>Micha'el achad hasarim hariishonim</em> (Michael, one of the chief princes): Michael is the guardian of Israel (12:1), distinguished as a chief-prince among the angelic order.</p>",
"14": "<p><strong>ubate anah lehaskil et asher-yiqreh le'amecha b'acharit hayamim</strong>: 'I have come to make you understand what is to happen to your people in the latter days.' <em>B'acharit hayamim</em> (H319 + H3117, in the latter/last days): the prophetic eschatological phrase marking the vision as concerning the end of the present age — the same phrase as Gen 49:1; Num 24:14; Isa 2:2; Mic 4:1. The vision is explicitly oriented toward eschatology, not merely near-term political history. <em>Ki od chazot layamim</em>: 'for the vision concerns days to come.'</p>",
"15": "<p><strong>uvedabro immi divarim elleh natati panai artsah ve'nilmeti</strong>: 'When he spoke these words to me, I turned my face toward the ground and was speechless.' The prophetic collapse at the content of the heavenly message (not merely the appearance of the heavenly being) deepens the encounter: the revelation itself, not just the revealer, overwhelms. <em>Nilmeti</em> (H481, became silent/speechless) — the speechlessness of profound awe and inadequacy before divine disclosure.</p>",
"16": "<p><strong>venogea kamareh benei adam al-sefatai eftach peh va'adabera</strong>: 'One having the appearance of the sons of man touched my lips, and I opened my mouth and spoke.' The touch on the lips echoes Isaiah's commission (Isa 6:7 — the coal touched to Isaiah's lips), enabling prophetic speech from one who had been silenced. The restoration of prophetic voice through divine touch is the pattern: God prepares the instrument of his word by touching the very organ of speech.</p>",
"17": "<p><strong>veich yuchal eved Adonai zeh ledabber im-Adonai zeh</strong>: 'How can the servant of my Lord speak with this lord of mine?' The double <em>Adonai</em>/<em>Adon</em> creates a reverential rhetorical question: the servant-status of Daniel before the heavenly messenger makes speech feel impossible. The phrase <em>eved Adonai</em> (servant of the Lord) is also the Isaianic designation for the suffering Servant — Daniel's self-identification places him within that tradition of covenant mediation.</p>",
"18": "<p><strong>vayosef vayigga bi kemar'eh ha'adam vayechazqeni</strong>: 'And again one having the appearance of a man touched me and strengthened me.' The second touch — now explicitly strengthening (<em>chazaq</em>, H2388) rather than silencing — restores the capacity to receive and transmit the revelation. <em>Chazaq</em> (be strong, strengthen) will recur in 10:19 as the thematic summary of what the heavenly visitation accomplishes for the prophet: Al-tira, shalom lach, chazaq vehitchazaq (Do not fear, peace to you, be strong and strong).</p>",
"19": "<p><strong>al-tira ish chamudot shalom lach chazaq vehitchazaq</strong>: 'Do not be afraid, O man greatly beloved. Peace to you; be strong and be strong.' The triple commissioning formula: no fear, peace, and double <em>chazaq</em>. The Hiphil <em>chazaq</em> + Hitpael <em>hitchazaq</em> creates an active and reflexive pairing: both made strong (by God) and actively strengthen yourself. <em>Shalom lach</em> (peace to you) is the greeting of completion and wholeness — the same shalom that marks covenant restoration. Gabriel's parting gift to the prophet is not information but the disposition needed to bear it.</p>",
"20": "<p><strong>ata ashuv lehilachem im-sar Paras veani yotze vehinei sar Yavan ba</strong>: 'I will return to fight against the prince of Persia; and when I go out, behold, the prince of Greece will come.' The cosmic geography of heavenly-earthly correspondence: <em>sar Paras</em> (prince of Persia) is replaced by <em>sar Yavan</em> (prince of Greece/Javan) — the Macedonian empire's rise is already visible in heaven before it appears on earth. The angelic battles are the heavenly dimension of the terrestrial empires — Persia falls because its heavenly prince is defeated; Greece rises because its prince overcomes.</p>",
"21": "<p><strong>efes ki agid lach et-harashum bichtav emet ve'ein echad mitchazaq immi al-eleh ki im-Michael sarcem</strong>: 'But I will tell you what is inscribed in the book of truth: there is none who contends by my side against these except Michael, your prince.' <em>Ketav emet</em> (book/writing of truth): a heavenly register of predetermined events — the eschatological script that Gabriel reads from. <em>Michael sarcem</em> (Michael your prince) — Israel has its own heavenly guardian, the chief angel Michael (12:1), who alone among the heavenly princes stands with Gabriel against the opposing national angels. Israel's protection is personal and angelic.</p>"
},
"11": {
"1": "<p><strong>vaani bishnat achat leDaryavesh haMadai amodeti lemachaziq ulema'oz lo</strong>: 'And in the first year of Darius the Mede, I stood up to confirm and strengthen him.' The angelic speaker continues — this verse is the end of Gabriel's explanation, linking the heavenly guardian's role to the transition from Babylonian to Median-Persian rule. The heavenly figure's reinforcing activity occurs at the empire's transition, supporting the cosmic order behind the earthly political change.</p>",
"2": "<p><strong>ve'attah emet agid lach hinei od shloshah melachim omdim leParas</strong>: 'And now I will tell you the truth: Behold, three more kings shall arise in Persia.' The predictive schema is historically specific: the three kings after Cyrus are Cambyses, Pseudo-Smerdis/Bardiya, and Darius I (or Cambyses, Darius I, Xerxes depending on reckoning). The fourth who is richer than all — Xerxes I (486-465 BCE) — led the massive invasion of Greece (480 BCE). <em>Yachaziq hakol et-malkhut Yavan</em> (stirring up all against the kingdom of Greece): Xerxes' Persian Wars are the historical turning point that made Greece the successor power.</p>",
"3": "<p><strong>veamad melek gibor umashel mimshel rab ve'asah kirtsono</strong>: 'And a mighty king shall arise who shall rule with great dominion and do as he wills.' <em>Gibor</em> (H1368, mighty one/warrior): the term applied to Alexander the Great — the single most decisive military figure of the ancient world, who conquered the Persian empire in under a decade (336-323 BCE). <em>Ve'asah kirtsono</em> (did according to his will) — the language of absolute uncontested sovereignty used later for Antiochus IV (v.36) and the eschatological king. Alexander as the type of the self-willed conqueror is established here.</p>",
"4": "<p><strong>uveoamdo tishshaver malkhuto vetechelets le'arba ruchot hashamayim</strong>: 'And as soon as he has arisen, his kingdom shall be broken and divided toward the four winds of heaven.' The sudden death of Alexander (323 BCE) at age 32 and the immediate fragmentation of his empire into four kingdoms (the Diadochi — Ptolemy in Egypt, Seleucus in Syria/East, Cassander in Macedonia, Lysimachus in Thrace) is one of the most precisely fulfillable prophecies in the OT. <em>Lo le'acharito velo kemoshlo asher mashal</em>: not to his descendants, nor with authority like his — Alexander left no effective successor.</p>",
"5": "<p><strong>veyechezaq melek haNegev</strong>: 'The king of the south shall be strong.' <em>Melek haNegev</em> (king of the south): Ptolemy I Soter of Egypt (305-283 BCE). <em>Melek haTzafon</em> (king of the north): Seleucus I Nicator (305-281 BCE) who took control of the largest Diadochi fragment. The two competing dynasties — Ptolemies vs. Seleucids — will dominate the next hundred years of political history narrated in vv. 5-35, with the land of Israel caught between them as the geographic and strategic corridor.</p>",
"6": "<p><strong>uveketz shanim yitchaberu</strong>: 'After some years they shall make an alliance.' The diplomatic marriage between the two dynasties: Berenice daughter of Ptolemy II married Antiochus II Theos (the Seleucid king, vv. 6-7) ca. 252 BCE. <em>Lo tachaziq koach hazroa</em> (she shall not retain the strength of her arm): Berenice and her father and child were all murdered when Antiochus II restored his first wife Laodice (246 BCE). Political marriage as a covenant-mechanism is exposed here as fragile — human alliances cannot sustain themselves without deeper covenantal foundations.</p>",
"7": "<p><strong>veamad minetzur shorsheha al-kano</strong>: 'One from the branch of her roots shall arise in his place.' Ptolemy III Euergetes, Berenice's brother, succeeded his father (Ptolemy II) and invaded the Seleucid kingdom in revenge, penetrating as far as Seleucia-on-the-Tigris (the Third Syrian War, 246-241 BCE). The image of the branch/shoot from the royal root (<em>netzur</em>) echoes the Isaianic netzur imagery of the Davidic shoot (Isa 11:1 — a shoot from the stump of Jesse) — though here applied to a foreign king, not messianically.</p>",
"8": "<p><strong>vegam eloheihem im nasichehem im-keli chemdatam kesef vezahav yishbeh Mitsrayim</strong>: 'He shall also carry off to Egypt their gods with their metal images and their precious vessels of silver and gold.' Ptolemy III is said to have brought back to Egypt many cult statues previously taken to Babylon — the return of divine images was a powerful political-theological statement in the ancient Near East (cf. Cyrus returning the temple vessels to Jerusalem, Ezra 1:7-11). The gods themselves are carried as spoil, demonstrating the political victors' control over divine protection.</p>",
"9": "<p><strong>uva bemamlekhet melek haNegev veshuv el-admato</strong>: 'Then the latter shall come into the realm of the king of the south but shall return to his own land.' The mutual incursions between Ptolemaic and Seleucid kingdoms — each advancing, then retreating — mark the ongoing warfare. The cyclical nature of these conflicts, each leaving the fundamental power balance unchanged, reflects the vanity of military conquest apart from the divine decree that will eventually settle all earthly kingdoms.</p>",
"10": "<p><strong>uvanav yitgaru veasafu hamon chayalot rabbot</strong>: 'His sons shall wage war and assemble a multitude of great forces.' Antiochus III the Great (Seleucus III's successor) resumed the Syrian Wars, advancing through Palestine in the Fourth Syrian War (219-217 BCE) until defeated by Ptolemy IV at Raphia (217 BCE). <em>Ve'avar veshataf ve'ashuv</em> (he shall pass through, be swept away, and return) — the military flood-metaphor for advancing armies is the Isaianic image of the Assyrian invasion (Isa 8:7-8 — overflows and passes on).</p>",
"11": "<p><strong>veyitmarer melek haNegev</strong>: 'The king of the south shall be enraged.' Ptolemy IV's response to Antiochus III's advance — mobilizing a large force and winning at Raphia (217 BCE). Despite the large numbers mobilized, the victory did not consolidate Egyptian strength. <em>Ki ya'amod hamon gadol</em>: the great multitude is given into the hand of the victor, but the victory is incomplete — Ptolemy IV failed to capitalize strategically.</p>",
"12": "<p><strong>venasei hehamon yarumam vilvavo</strong>: 'When he has taken away the multitude, his heart shall be exalted.' Pride following military victory — the consistent biblical dynamic where success leads to hubris (cf. Deut 8:14; 2 Chr 26:16 on Uzziah). Ptolemy IV returned to Egypt after Raphia without pressing his advantage, and his reign declined. <em>Vehippil rebebot velo ya'oz</em>: he shall strike down tens of thousands yet shall not prevail — the decisive victory that fails to consolidate is a recurring historical pattern.</p>",
"13": "<p><strong>veshav melek haTzafon vehe'emid hamon rab</strong>: 'For the king of the north shall again raise a great multitude.' Antiochus III regrouped and, after Ptolemy IV's death (204 BCE) and the accession of the child Ptolemy V, renewed his campaign — the Fifth Syrian War (202-195 BCE), capturing Palestine. <em>Uveketz ha'ittim shanim</strong>: after the appointed time — <em>et</em> (H6256) as the appointed/appropriate time, the same term used for YHWH's kairos moments throughout the prophets. History moves on YHWH's timeline, not human ambition.</p>",
"14": "<p><strong>uveat hahi rabbim yaqumu al-melek haNegev uvnei paritsei amcha yinasu lehakim chazun venichshalu</strong>: 'In those times many shall rise against the king of the south, and the violent ones among your own people shall lift themselves up in order to fulfill the vision, but they shall fail.' <em>Bnei paritzei amcha</em> (the violent ones of your people): Jewish pro-Seleucid factions who collaborated with Antiochus III, believing his conquest would fulfill the restoration prophecies. Their failure — <em>venichshalu</em> (they stumbled/fell) — illustrates the danger of presuming to force prophetic fulfillment through political-military action.</p>",
"15": "<p><strong>uveshavat ir hamivtzarot velo yaamdur zeroa haNegev</strong>: 'The king of the north shall come and cast up siege works and take a well-fortified city.' Sidon fell to Antiochus III in 198 BCE; the Egyptian general Scopas was defeated at Panion and besieged at Sidon. <em>Zeroa</em> (H2220, arm/strength): the military arm metaphor — Egypt's arm proved insufficient against the Seleucid advance. The arm/strength of earthly powers is consistently shown as inadequate in Daniel's vision.</p>",
"16": "<p><strong>veyaas haba elav kirtsono ve'ein oamed lefanav</strong>: 'He who comes against him shall do as he wills, and none shall stand before him.' Antiochus III's unchecked advance through Palestine after 198 BCE. <em>Eretz haTzvi</em> (the beautiful/glorious land): the standard prophetic designation for the land of Israel (Ezek 20:6, 15; Jer 3:19; Dan 8:9; 11:41) — the land that becomes the arena of competing imperial ambitions throughout vv. 5-35.</p>",
"17": "<p><strong>veyasem panav lavo bteqeph kol malkhuto</strong>: 'He shall set his face to come with the strength of his whole kingdom.' Antiochus III's diplomatic strategy — marrying his daughter Cleopatra I to the young Ptolemy V (193 BCE), hoping she would serve his interests in Egypt. <em>Uvat hanashim yitennah lo lehashchitah</strong>: he shall give him a daughter of women to destroy him, but it shall not stand. Cleopatra I proved loyal to Egypt, not her father. The marriage-alliance strategy — using a daughter as a political weapon — illustrates the instrumentalization of persons in power politics, which Daniel's vision exposes as ultimately futile.</p>",
"18": "<p><strong>veyasev panav le'iyim ulakad rabbim</strong>: 'He shall turn his face to the coastlands and shall capture many of them.' Antiochus III's western campaigns (196-191 BCE) into Asia Minor and the Aegean islands, bringing him into conflict with Rome. <em>Veheshiv lo cherpo</em> (a commander shall put an end to his insolence): the Roman commander Lucius Cornelius Scipio Asiaticus defeated Antiochus III at Magnesia (190 BCE) — the first decisive Roman intervention in the eastern Mediterranean, signaling Rome's future imperial dominance.</p>",
"19": "<p><strong>veyasev panav lema'uzzei artzo venikhshal venapal velo yimmatze</strong>: 'Then he shall turn his face back toward the fortresses of his own land, but he shall stumble and fall, and shall not be found.' Antiochus III's humiliating retreat after Magnesia, his attempt to plunder a temple in Elymais to restore his depleted treasury (187 BCE), and his assassination there — the great Seleucid king ended obscurely. The language <em>velo yimmatze</em> (and shall not be found) suggests sudden disappearance from history's stage — a warning to all who trust in military strength.</p>",
"20": "<p><strong>veamad al-kanno over nogesh heder malkhut</strong>: 'In his place one shall arise who shall send an exactor of tribute through the glory of the kingdom.' Seleucus IV Philopator (187-175 BCE) who sent Heliodorus to plunder the Jerusalem temple treasury (2 Macc 3) — the historical background for the Maccabean crisis. <em>Uvi'yamim achadim yishaber velo ve'aph beanaf velo bemilchamah</em>: he shall be broken within a few days, neither in anger nor in war. Heliodorus poisoned Seleucus IV — an undramatic end that nevertheless transferred power to Antiochus IV.</p>",
"21": "<p><strong>veamad al-kanno niv'zeh velo natenu alav hod malkhut</strong>: 'In his place shall arise a contemptible person to whom royal majesty has not been given.' <em>Niv'zeh</em> (H959, despised/held in contempt): the same root as Isa 53:3's <em>niv'zeh</em> — the despised servant. Here it describes Antiochus IV Epiphanes who was not the legitimate heir (the throne belonged to Demetrius, son of Seleucus IV, held as a Roman hostage). <em>Uvah beshilva vehecheziq malkhut bechalaqlaqot</em>: he shall come in time of security and obtain the kingdom by flatteries — the seizure of power through intrigue rather than legitimate succession.</p>",
"22": "<p><strong>uzeroa hashtetef yishtof milfanav veyishaveru</strong>: 'Armies shall be utterly swept away before him and broken, even the prince of the covenant.' <em>Nagid berit</em> (prince of the covenant): debated — either a Ptolemaic official or the high priest Onias III, who was removed from office by Antiochus IV's intrigues (2 Macc 4:7-10). The desacralization of the high priesthood — <em>nagid berit</em> (covenant-prince) eliminated — marks the beginning of Antiochus's assault on the covenantal order.</p>",
"23": "<p><strong>ume'hitchabro elav ya'aseh mirmah</strong>: 'After an alliance is made with him he shall act deceitfully.' <em>Mirmah</em> (H4820, deceit/treachery): Antiochus IV's characteristic political mode. The Ptolemaic alliance he entered only to betray marks the corruption of covenant-making — the very instrument of international relations (treaties) is weaponized through deception.</p>",
"24": "<p><strong>beshilvah uvimshmane medinah yavo</strong>: 'In a time of security he shall come into the richest parts of the province.' Antiochus IV's innovative strategy of winning loyalty through lavish distribution of plunder — unlike his predecessors he gave away what he had seized, buying support. <em>Veyachashor machashavot al-mivtzarim ve'ad et</em>: he shall devise plans against strongholds, but only for a time. The <em>et</em> (appointed time) limit frames all his activities within divine permission — he acts within time granted, not unlimited.</p>",
"25": "<p><strong>veyaer kocho ulvavo al-melek haNegev bechayil gadol</strong>: 'He shall stir up his power and his heart against the king of the south with a great army.' Antiochus IV's first Egyptian campaign (170-169 BCE). <em>Velo yaamood ki yachashvu alav machashavot</strong>: the Egyptian king shall not stand because plots shall be devised against him. The political betrayal by Egypt's own counselors mirrors the intrigue by which Antiochus himself seized power — the corruption spreads through all parties involved.</p>",
"26": "<p><strong>ve'ochelei patbago yishberuhu</strong>: 'The ones who eat his food shall break him.' The betrayal by court insiders — those who benefit from the king's table become the instruments of his downfall. The image of table-fellowship as the site of betrayal echoes the psalmist's lament (Ps 41:9 — the one who ate my bread lifted his heel against me) and anticipates the Judas-betrayal pattern. Inner circles are as dangerous as external enemies.</p>",
"27": "<p><strong>ushneihem hamelachim libbam lemira veal shulchan echad kazav yadaberu</strong>: 'And as for the two kings, their hearts shall be bent on doing evil. They shall speak lies at the same table.' The diplomatic fiction of negotiation as cover for mutual deception — both Antiochus IV and Ptolemy VI meet publicly as allies while planning against each other. <em>Velo titzlach ki od qetz lamoedh</em>: but it shall not succeed, for the end is yet to be at the time appointed. The divine <em>moedh</em> (appointed time) overrides all human plotting.</p>",
"28": "<p><strong>veyashov artzo birechush gadol ulvavo al-berit qodesh</strong>: 'And he shall return to his land with great wealth, but his heart shall be set against the holy covenant.' Antiochus IV's return from Egypt (169 BCE) with enormous plunder — including the pillaging of the Jerusalem temple (1 Macc 1:20-28; 2 Macc 5:15-21). <em>Berit qodesh</em> (holy covenant): the first explicit mention of the covenant as the target of Antiochus's hostility — not merely geopolitical rivalry but a theological-covenantal assault. The enemy of the people of God is ultimately the enemy of their covenant.</p>",
"29": "<p><strong>lamoedh yashuv uvah banegev velo tihyeh kharishon vekha'acharon</strong>: 'At the time appointed he shall return and come into the south, but it shall not be this time as it was before.' The second Egyptian campaign (168 BCE) was less successful — Antiochus IV was met at Eleusis by the Roman legate Gaius Popilius Laenas, who drew a circle in the sand around Antiochus and demanded he decide on peace before stepping out of the circle. Forced to withdraw, his frustration was redirected against Jerusalem.</p>",
"30": "<p><strong>uva bo tziyim Kittim venikh'ah veshav veza'am al-berit qodesh</strong>: 'For ships of Kittim shall come against him, and he shall be afraid and withdraw, and shall turn back and be enraged and take action against the holy covenant.' <em>Kittim</em> (H3794): originally Cypress, later used for western maritime powers — here Rome. The Roman humiliation at Eleusis is the turning point: unable to vent his fury on Rome, Antiochus redirected against the covenant people. <em>Veshav veham al-ozvei berit qodesh</em>: he shall pay attention to those who forsake the holy covenant — the Hellenizing Jewish collaborators who aided his assault on Judaism.</p>",
"31": "<p><strong>uzeroa mimenu yaamodu vechill'lu et-haMiqdash haMa'oz veheisiru hatamid venatenu hashiquts meshomem</strong>: 'Forces from him shall appear and profane the temple and fortress, and shall take away the regular burnt offering and set up the abomination that makes desolate.' <em>Hasorim hatamid</em> (removing the regular/continual offering): Antiochus IV abolished the daily tamid sacrifice in Kislev 167 BCE (1 Macc 1:39, 45). <em>Shiquts meshomem</em> (abomination of desolation): the altar of Zeus Olympios erected on the altar of burnt offering (1 Macc 1:54; 2 Macc 6:2) — Jesus identifies this as the signal for the eschatological tribulation (Mark 13:14).</p>",
"32": "<p><strong>umarishiei berit yachanif bechalaqlaqot veyodei Elohav yacharziqu veasu</strong>: 'He shall seduce with flattery those who violate the covenant, but the people who know their God shall stand firm and take action.' <em>Yodei Eloheihem</em> (those who know their God): <em>yada</em> (H3045, know) as covenantal intimacy and experiential relationship — not merely intellectual knowledge but the deep personal knowledge of a people in covenant. <em>Yacharziqu veasu</em>: they shall stand firm and act — the combination of interior resolve and exterior witness marks the Maccabean faithful as the paradigm for covenant loyalty under pressure.</p>",
"33": "<p><strong>umaskilei am yavinu larabim venikhshalu beherev uvelehavah bishvi uvevizah yamim</strong>: 'And the wise among the people shall make many understand, though for some days they shall stumble by sword and flame, by captivity and plunder.' <em>Maskilei am</em> (those who make wise among the people): <em>maskil</em> from <em>sakal</em> (H7919, be prudent/give insight) — the teacher-sages who help the community understand what is happening in light of covenant history. Their ministry costs them severely — sword, flame, captivity, plunder. The teacher of truth in a hostile empire bears the cost of fidelity.</p>",
"34": "<p><strong>ubehibashalam yee'zeru ezra me'at venitlavu aleihem rabbim bachalaqlaqot</strong>: 'When they stumble, they shall receive a little help. And many shall join themselves to them with flattery.' <em>Ezra me'at</em> (a little help): the Maccabean revolt (begun 167 BCE) is described with striking understatement — not the glorious deliverance but only modest assistance, with opportunists joining insincerely. The phrase <em>bachalaqlaqot</em> (with flatteries) — the same root used for Antiochus's intrigue (v.21) now characterizing those who attach to the faithful cause for self-protection.</p>",
"35": "<p><strong>umin hamaskilim yikashlu letzaref bahem ulvarer ullilaben ad-et qetz</strong>: 'And some of the wise shall stumble, so that they may be refined, purified, and made white, until the time of the end, for it is yet for the time appointed.' The suffering of the righteous teachers is explicitly purposive: <em>letzaref</em> (to refine like metal), <em>levarer</em> (to purify), <em>lillaben</em> (to make white). Three metallurgical-laundering metaphors for the purification that persecution produces (cf. Mal 3:3; 1 Pet 1:7). <em>Ki od lamo'ed</em>: the suffering is bounded — the appointed time limits all persecution.</p>",
"36": "<p><strong>veyitromem veyitgadal al-kol-El veal El Elim yedabber niflaot</strong>: 'And the king shall do as he wills. He shall exalt himself and magnify himself above every god, and shall speak astonishing things against the God of gods.' <em>Yitromem veyitgadal</em>: both Hitpael (reflexive) verbs — self-exaltation doubled. <em>Niflaot</em> (H6381, wonders/monstrous things/things beyond capacity): the claim to divine status and power beyond what any human can legitimately claim. This verse transitions from the historical Antiochus IV to what many interpreters read as a typological figure — the eschatological self-divinizing power (cf. 2 Thess 2:3-4; Rev 13:5-6) who recapitulates Antiochus's pattern at history's end.</p>",
"37": "<p><strong>veal Elohei avotav lo yavin veal chemdath nashim</strong>: 'He shall pay no attention to the gods of his fathers, or to the one beloved by women.' <em>Elohei avotav</em> (gods of his fathers): abandoning ancestral religion — Antiochus IV adopted the cult of Zeus Olympios and demanded divine worship for himself. <em>Chemdath nashim</em> (desire/beloved of women): the most natural reading is Adonis/Tammuz, the dying-and-rising deity widely mourned by women (cf. Ezek 8:14 — women weeping for Tammuz). Antiochus's religious innovations eliminated even this popular cult. The eschatological king abandons all prior religious loyalties in pursuit of absolute self-divinization.</p>",
"38": "<p><strong>veal-Elohei ma'uzim al kanno yechabbed</strong>: 'He shall honor the god of fortresses instead of these.' <em>Elohei ma'uzim</em> (god of fortresses/strongholds): the deity of military power — possibly Mars/Ares or Jupiter Capitolinus, or simply the raw power of military force. The eschatological king worships raw power — not as means to an end but as ultimate value. This is the logic of empire stripped of its religious veneer: the only god that matters is the god who gives military victory.</p>",
"39": "<p><strong>ve'asah lemivatsei ma'uzim im-elohah nechar</strong>: 'He shall deal with the strongest fortresses with the help of a foreign god.' The combination of military strategy and religious innovation — using new religious incentives (<em>yarbeh kavod</em>, increase honor) to motivate soldiers. <em>Vehimshilan barabim vechamat adamah yechalek bishcar</em>: dividing the land as a bribe. The monetization of loyalty through territorial grants marks the transactional politics of totalitarian power.</p>",
"40": "<p><strong>ubeet qetz yitnagach imo melek haNegev</strong>: 'At the time of the end, the king of the south shall attack him.' The <em>et qetz</em> (time of the end) marks the transition to eschatological horizon — whether continuing the Antiochus IV narrative or moving to a future figure who recapitulates his pattern. The military flood-metaphor resumes: <em>yishtatef ba'aratzot</em> (overflow through many countries) — the Assyrian/Babylonian flood-image (Isa 8:7-8; Dan 9:26) applied to the final military campaign.</p>",
"41": "<p><strong>uvoa b'Eretz haTzvi verobot yikashelu</strong>: 'He shall come into the beautiful land, and tens of thousands shall fall.' <em>Eretz haTzvi</em> (the beautiful/desirable land) recurs as the focal point — the land of covenant, which becomes the eschatological battle-ground. <em>Ve'eleh yimatlu miyado Edom uMo'av ureishit Bnei Ammon</em>: Edom, Moab, and the firstfruits of Ammon escape — traditional Israel-enemies who are preserved, paradoxically, when Israel suffers. The selectivity of eschatological judgment preserves historical irony.</p>",
"42": "<p><strong>viyishllach yado ba'aratzot uEretz Mitsrayim lo tihyeh liphletah</strong>: 'He shall stretch out his hand against the countries, and the land of Egypt shall not escape.' <em>Shalach yad</em> (stretch out the hand) is the Exodus-language of YHWH's powerful intervention (Exod 3:20; 7:5) — the eschatological conqueror appropriates the Exodus gesture of divine action for his own military campaign, the ultimate parody of divine power.</p>",
"43": "<p><strong>umashol bemiqdanot hazahav vekheseph uvechol chamudot Mitsrayim</strong>: 'He shall become ruler of the treasures of gold and of silver, and all the precious things of Egypt.' The wealth of empires — gold, silver, precious things — that Daniel's vision catalogs through eleven chapters is ultimately exposed as transient. The rich nations that trusted their treasuries are stripped. <em>Valuvim uKushim bimitzadav</em>: the Libyans and Cushites following in his train — the widest geographic extent of the final empire's dominion, reaching Egypt and its African dependencies.</p>",
"44": "<p><strong>vishmuot yebahaluhu mizrach utzafon veyatze bechemah gedolah</strong>: 'But news from the east and the north shall alarm him, and he shall go out with great fury to destroy and devote many to destruction.' The reversal: at the moment of maximum expansion, alarming news from flank regions creates the conditions for the conqueror's undoing. <em>Lehashmid ulehachriem rabbim</em> (to destroy and devote many to destruction): the <em>cherem</em> (H2763, sacred destruction/ban) language of holy war — the total-destruction devoted to the deity. The final military campaign employs the vocabulary of sacred destruction, the ultimate parody of covenant warfare.</p>",
"45": "<p><strong>veyita oholei apadno bein yamim lehar tzevi qodesh</strong>: 'And he shall pitch his palatial tents between the sea and the glorious holy mountain.' The eschatological conqueror establishes his camp between the Mediterranean and the Temple Mount — the geographically and theologically central location of the cosmos in biblical geography. <em>Uvah ad-qitzo ve'ein ozer lo</em>: 'Yet he shall come to his end, with none to help him.' The three-word oracle — <em>qitzo ve'ein ozer</em> — is the anti-climax of the entire chapter's imperial narrative: the self-divinizing conqueror dies without help, alone, the way every absolute power ends. YHWH's <em>moedh</em> (appointed time) has the last word.</p>"
}
}

